sec.p:
All analyses were conducted using R 2.14.1 (R Development Core Team). Linear Mixed Models (
   Bates et al., 2009) started with a model including all of the fixed terms and interactions of interest (maximal model), followed by stepwise removal of each term in the order which resulted in the least significant change in deviance using a likelihood-ratio test for model comparison, until the minimal adequate model was found (when only significant terms remained; 
   Crawley, 2007). The significance of explanatory variables was determined by testing for the change in deviance in the fit of the model when the term was removed from the model. Repeated measures of groups and individuals were controlled for as required, by fitting group and individual identity as random terms, as detailed below. The residuals were checked for normality and homoscedasticity, and if they did not meet these assumptions the response terms were transformed to resolve this (see details below).
